		<!-- Information Stuff -->
		<td class="main_font" width="100%">


								
								
			<!-- Begin News/Information Section -->
				<table border="0" width="100%" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" ID="Table23">
					<tr id="trmasthead">
						<td valign="middle" class="main_font" align="center">
							<font size="3"><b>&nbsp;</b></font>
					    </td>
					</tr>
					
					   <td>

			
			
			


<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%">
<tr>
	<td width="1%">&nbsp;</td>
	<td width="98%">

		<table width="100%">
		<tr>
			<td>
				<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="3"><b>    Druid Guide</b></font>
					<br>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">
					<b><A href="mailto: "> </a> | 
		            4/8/1999 5:01:59 PM</b></font></p>
		         <a href="guides.asp">
		         <font face="verdana" size="2">Return to guide listing.</font></a>
					
					<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">The Druid class is very appealing to any player who enjoys a mix of self-sufficiency with the opportunity to be a truly excellent cooperative player.  The thing to remember is that you have to make a number of significant compromises--but the payoff is incredibly satisfying if you're willing to invest the time.  Much of this commentary will end up including specifics about Surefall Glade--the home of Human and Half-Elf Druids.  While I look forward to visiting Rivervale and the home of my Wood-Elf brothers, I can only lend specific advice on the terrain I know best.<BR>
<BR>
What skills you should practice:<BR>
*Decide on your weapon early.  The Druid's weapon skills grow slowly.  You start out with a club--so 1-H Blunt is a fine choice with decent weapons like the Screaming Mace showing up later in the game.  2-H Blunt lets you use a staff--which does more damage than a mace but doesn't allow you to carry a shield.  Many good staves &amp; crooks exist, so this is always a good choice but it's not going to help you with your first few levels unless someone gives you a staff right away.  The other choice is 1-H Slashing--but a Druid can only use the scimitar.  There is supposedly a Druid-only artifact-level scimitar--so this may be an interesting choice for those looking for something a bit non-routine.  1-3 practices at the first level you pick up the weapon are pretty good--you just have to get out there and use the skill then.<BR>
*You start out with the spells Minor Healing (Alteration) and Skin Like Wood (Abjuration).  Be sure to take a level in Alter and Abjure at your first level--and then practice practice practice.  Most skills for Druids max at 5*level + 5.  As you buy other spells, check their types and take only 1 practice in those skills.  Then practice.  There is never any need to purchase more than one practice in any magical skill.<BR>
*Some skills build very slowly to start--most notably Sense Heading and Forage.  Don't bother to buy more than 1 practice in Sense Heading--but do practice it constantly.  Forage is a tougher choice--it grows very slowly and takes a long time to practice.  You might be more pleased with additional practices if you have any to spare.<BR>
*Fishing is your friend.  Buy a rank as soon as you can spare--and then save your pennies for a pole and bait.  You're going to spend a lot of time practicing your spells and secondary skills.  You might as well earn a few gold while you're at it.<BR>
*Vocational skills, like tailoring, smithing, pottery, etc. are expensive to fail at.  Spend all of your extra practices on the one you are currently working at--and concentrate on only one at a time.<BR>
<BR>
Levels 1-3<BR>
Before you head out, be sure to scribe and memorize your spells.  Cast them a couple times to get the feel for how they work.  You begin your hunt (if you're starting from Surefall Glade) in Qeynos Hills--which is located thru the very long, very dark tunnel.  Human players should be sure to equip their candles for that first trip--and once out in the Hills, ask if someone will get you a Fire Beetle eye which is a far superior light source (and a neccesary component for the Flame Lick spell).  Stick to bats, rats, snakes, gnoll pups and decaying skels.  The Fire Beetles look cool--but they're much better armored and will gang up.  Wait til 2 or 3 to start experimenting with them.  Gnoll Pups and Decaying Skeletons are the most likely to drop equip and pricey items for resale--so nab them when you can.  In fact, you should be saving up for your first purchased spell: Burst of Flame (Evocation).  This is a tiny little direct damage spell that would be laughable to a magician or wizard--but fret not.  It's purpose is not to do damage--but to reel in opponents from a range.  No more running hither and non trying to line up perfectly with an opponent.  Zap them and they come to you.  Hunting really speeds up then. Watch out for skeletons and mangy rats--they are aggressive and have an annoying habit of strolling thru your best hunting grounds.<BR>
<BR>
Levels 4+<BR>
It's harder to get experience now.  My suggestion is that you purchase the spell Sense Animals (Divination).  This will locate animals for you.  Then team up with a Ranger.  Rangers have the same faction as you for the most part--and animals will not attack you unprovoked.  So together, Druids and Rangers can safely walk amid the wolves, bears, rabid wolves and rabid grizzlies that vex so many other players.  Now essentially find a rich area for the next tier of opponents--my suggestion in Qeynos Hills is the ridge immediately to your right as you leave the Glade entrance...go past the lake and patrol the ridge that runs from the lake to Qeynos itself.  You'll find lots of large snakes, large bats, giant rats, gnoll scouts amid the wolves and bears.  Watch out for the skels--they sometimes gang up.  The trick to the Druid/Ranger combo is this--you locate the prey using Sense Animals and just eyeballing, and the Ranger tracks you to keep up.  This is important.  The Ranger will try to suggest that he should track animals--but if you try that, you will lose the Ranger over and over and over again.  The hills and zigs and zags in that valley means disappearing group members.  But a Ranger can follow your tracks.  You initiate the battle with Burst of Flame (or something more impressive if you wish) and then the Ranger finishes the kill.  Hopefully, your Ranger buddy will take this chance to practice his Taunt skill to keep you from getting killed.  Use Shield and Heal liberally to make it worth your group's time.<BR>
Later you'll be choosing between BlackBurrow and the Plains of Karanis.  The Plains are ideal for Druid/Ranger groups of 3 or more from level 6 on up.  BlackBurrow is ... well, it's crowded and full of trains of death and players who poach your kills and ... mostly it's just nasty.  However, it's good for your Faction standing to go there.  Find a good group who you can trust--again, level 6 and up.  Work together because, altho there are many exceptions, something about that dungeon brings out the worst in the selfish players.  
			<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
					</p>
			</td>
				<td>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</td></tr>
